i'm running kanata as a systemd user service. how restart with this new keymap?

Gemini said
Since you're running it as a systemd user service, you don't need to mess with sudo or global system processes. You can handle this entirely from your standard terminal.

The Command
Run this to reload the config and restart the service:

Bash
systemctl --user restart kanata.service
Pro-Tips for Managing Your Service
Check for Errors: If your keys suddenly stop working or don't change, Kanata might have hit a syntax error in your new .kbd file. Check the logs with:

Bash
journalctl --user -u kanata.service -f
(The -f flag follows the logs in real-time, which is great for debugging while you're editing.)

Automatic Reloads: If you get tired of manually restarting, most people use the -w (watch) flag in their service's ExecStart line (e.g., ExecStart=/usr/bin/kanata -c /path/to/config.kbd -w). This tells Kanata to automatically reload every time you save the file.

One Last Check
Before you restart, double-check that your config.kbd file is actually named what the service expects (usually config.kbd or kanata.kbd) and is in the right folder (typically ~/.config/kanata/).

